<section xml:id="subsec-1-3-2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <p>There are a number of logical equivalences that are important to become familiar with. If you don't understand why any of the following are equivalent statements, try building a truth table!</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Double negation: <m>\sim (\sim P)\equiv P</m></li>
        <li>
            <p>Commutativity:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><m>P\wedge Q\equiv Q\wedge P</m></li>
                <li><m>P\vee Q\equiv Q\vee P</m></li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>Distributivity:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><m>P\wedge (Q\vee R)\equiv (P\wedge Q)\vee (P\wedge R)</m></li>
                <li><m>P\vee (Q\wedge R)\equiv (P\vee Q)\wedge (P\vee R)</m></li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>Absorption:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><m>P\vee P\equiv P</m></li>
                <li><m>P\wedge P\equiv P</m></li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>De Morgan's Law:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><m>\sim (P\vee Q)\equiv (\sim P)\wedge (\sim Q)</m></li>
                <li><m>\sim (P\wedge Q)\equiv (\sim P)\vee (\sim Q)</m></li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>Associativity:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><m>(P\vee Q)\vee R\equiv P\vee (Q\vee R)</m></li>
                <li><m>(P\wedge Q)\wedge R\equiv P\wedge (Q\wedge R)</m></li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Rob's Law: <m>P\implies Q\equiv (\sim P)\vee Q</m></li>
    </ul>

</section>